The principal asked three questions and gave candy to the children who answered yes. We need to determine how many pieces of candy the principal gave to the truth-tellers. 1. **Truth-tellers (T)**: Answered yes to Q1, no to Q2, and no to Q3. 2. **Liars (L)**: Answered no to Q1, no to Q2, and yes to Q3. 3. **Alternaters starting with truth (A1)**: Answered no to Q1, no to Q2, and yes to Q3. 4. **Alternaters starting with lies (A2)**: Answered no to Q1, yes to Q2, and no to Q3. Given: - 22 children answered yes to Q1. - 15 children answered yes to Q2. - 9 children answered yes to Q3. Key equations: 1. Total children: \( T + L + A1 + A2 = 31 \) 2. Q1 Yes: \( T + L + A1 = 22 \) 3. Q2 Yes: \( A2 + L = 15 \) 4. Q3 Yes: \( L + A1 = 9 \) Solving these equations: - From equation 4: \( L + A1 = 9 \) implies \( A1 = 9 - L \). - From equation 3: \( A2 + L = 15 \) implies \( A2 = 15 - L \). - Substituting \( A1 \) and \( A2 \) into equation 2: \( T + L + (9 - L) = 22 \) implies \( T + 9 = 22 \) hence \( T = 13 \). - Substituting \( L = 6 \) (from equation 4: \( 6 + A1 = 9 \) implies \( A1 = 3 \)). - Verifying with equation 1: \( 13 + 6 + 3 + 9 = 31 \). Thus, the number of pieces of candy given to truth-tellers is \( T = 13 \). \[ \boxed{13} \]
